<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between decimal degrees and DMS?", answer: "Decimal degrees express latitude and longitude as a single floating-point number per axis, for example 40.7128 for New York's latitude. Degrees-minutes-seconds (DMS) breaks the same angle into three components: whole degrees, arc minutes (sixtieths of a degree), and arc seconds (sixtieths of a minute), plus a hemisphere letter. Decimal degrees are easier to store and compute with, while DMS is the traditional format on navigation charts and older maps." },
  { question: "How do I convert DMS to decimal degrees manually?", answer: "Take the degrees, add the minutes divided by 60, add the seconds divided by 3600, and apply a negative sign if the hemisphere is South or West. For example, 40°42'46\"N becomes 40 + 42/60 + 46/3600 = 40.7128 degrees. This calculator does the arithmetic for you and also does the reverse conversion from decimal back to DMS." },
  { question: "Which format should I use?", answer: "Use decimal degrees for software, GPS devices, APIs, and spreadsheets, because every modern system accepts them as a single number and they are easier to sort and compare. Use DMS when reading nautical charts, USGS topographic maps, aviation sectionals, or older surveying documents, which still display coordinates in the traditional three-part format. Many apps let you switch between the two in their settings." },
  { question: "What do the N, S, E, W letters mean?", answer: "N (North) and S (South) indicate whether a latitude is in the Northern or Southern Hemisphere, and E (East) and W (West) indicate whether a longitude is east or west of the prime meridian. In decimal form, northern latitudes are positive and southern latitudes are negative, while eastern longitudes are positive and western longitudes are negative. Hemisphere letters remove that sign convention from the number itself." },
  { question: "How precise is one arc second?", answer: "One arc second of latitude is about 30.87 meters on the ground, and one arc second of longitude is about 30.87 × cos(latitude) meters, which shrinks as you move toward the poles. Six decimal places of decimal degrees give you roughly 0.11 meter resolution, which is enough for most surveying and all consumer mapping uses." }
]) %>

